replies.comment info:
@Angelina I agree with you. There was definitely a drastic increase between the year of 2022 and 2023. 
I also wonder how people were being affected during this time period, was there any change? 
I also agree with the fact that it does in fact affect my community now as well COVID is certainly still a virus that being spread around. May not be as bad as before but people can still be affected by it.

@Samuel 
Mistake in headline should be 
Looming Effects of Disease: Coronavirus Coming Back for More?

@Yaemmy 
I'm curious to hear what you define as the time period of the Pandemic. You refer to it in your opening sentence of your notice and I'm interested to hear what your thoughts are. There definitely seem to be different spikes. When you look at spikes, are you considering the highest spike? Or any spike in the data? 

I'd love to hear your thoughts.

@Vivian 
You make a good point about this affecting the community by increasing the number of people in the hospitals needing resources related to respiratory care. How does this affect staffing and supply chain issues?

You mention average number of hospital visits, but what do you mean by "average"? Since this title specifically mentions "percent of weekly doctor and hospital visits", is it the average percentage of people at a point in time?

@Andrea Sierra Period 5 
I'm really interested in your wondering. We don't have a full knowledge of the long term effects of COVID and you picked up on that in your writing.

Could you follow up with how you define a surge? You mention a "surge of cases around January." I'd like to hear more about how you define this.

@SophiaV AOSE 
I appreciate the trends that you noticed. When you mention doctor/hospital visits for respiratory illness, is that what the title of the graph implies?

Your wondering about if people were scared to seek care because of COVID could be very valid. COVID was so new during 2020-2021 and we had so many concerns about what we didn't know.

@Emma B AOSE 
So many great noticings about trends over time and how they compare to each other. Your observations about the heightened percentage of doctor/hospital visits related to respiratory illness during winter months makes me curious about what you predict the trend may look like in the coming months.

You mentioned that in your community, the first people to quarantine were those with respiratory conditions such as asthma. Are you starting to see those with these conditions feeling concerned? How do you think your community would respond to this graph and the data?

@Emma AOSE 
I noticed that you mentioned that you expected the "results to be flipped" of more people visiting doctors and hospitals for respiratory illness during 2020-2021. I think many people feel the same way. Is that what this graph is saying though? 
Notice the title of the graph: "Percent of weekly doctor and hospital visits for respiratory illnesses". Who is the population of people we looking at when we determine these percentages?

@Nicole 
I am interested in your wondering. It feels as if we as a culture still turn and look when we hear someone coughing. This may be, as you said, because "the pandemic has made individuals more conscious about their respiratory health." I wonder what is happening in your community. How are people responding to those around them who are getting sick? Do you see increased masking? Staying home when getting initial signs a respiratory illness? 
Since New York Times has such a wide audience, I'm curious to hear how places around the country are interacting with this data.
